{
  "texts": [
    "Such results are particularly relevant to identify the kernel-like representation [25] of the linearized operator.",
    "However, while they guarantee the existence of a spectral gap, they yield no information on its value, and quantifying λ in terms of the physical parameters of the problem is crucial to determine explicit rates of convergence to equilibrium [21,28,43,44].",
    "Our result provides this missing information.We prove Theorem 2 by adapting the arguments from [21,28] on the linearized Boltzmann operator for inert mixtures, where it is exploited the fact that L EL can be split into the sum L EL mono + L EL cross of two operators (respectively modeling elastic collisions between the same species or cross interactions between different species) such that L EL mono has an explicit spectral gap [4,42] and L EL cross is nonpositive.",
    "The reactive linearized Boltzmann operator L shares a similar structure: when computing its Dirichlet form, one has that L EL (f), fL 2 v µ -1 2satisfies inequality (27) with an explicit λ EL and we have seen that L CH (f), fL 2 v µ -1 2≤ 0.",
    "This negativity can be quantified in terms of an energy functional E(f), when looking at distributions that belong to Ker (L EL)."
  ]
}